segments.text: Our lives depend upon the ocean.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Dr. Sylvia Earle, National Geographic Explorer in Residence, and the first female chief scientist at NOAA, describes the ocean as the life support system for our blue planet.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: The ocean is the source of the air we breathe, the food we eat, the rain that makes our region green.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: More than half the world's oxygen comes from the ocean, and it controls our climate and weather.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: and some of the most biodiverse habitats on the planet are found in the ocean.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: 80% of it has yet to be explored.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Today, the ocean, including Puget Sound, is facing unprecedented threats that endanger all life on Earth, including ours.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: The ocean has already absorbed 90% of the excess heat from global warming, shielding us from its worst effects, but its capacity to continue absorbing heat is limited.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Industrial pollution, destructive overfishing, oil spills, noise, habitat loss all threaten our ocean.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: From coral bleaching to marine dead zones of low oxygen, the impact of these human activities is clear, accelerating extinction and destruction of vital ecosystems.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Despite these threats, less than 1% of the ocean is currently protected for marine life.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: We believe we can go and must go beyond simply limiting harm
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: and began to reverse the damage done to our ocean.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Our vision is regeneration, a new term for many.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: We can restore a healthy, flourishing ocean and leave our planet and our communities better than we found them.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Many of the solutions we'll need already exist, and more are rapidly developing.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: We've advanced renewable energy technologies to help reduce the use of fossil fuels.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Sustainable fishing techniques can restore healthy fisheries and ensure food security for coastal communities.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Conservation efforts are beginning to show astounding success in reversing the loss of species and restoring biodiversity.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: At the Seattle Aquarium, our mission is to inspire conservation of our marine environment.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: The aquarium is the largest marine conservation institution in the Northwestern United States.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: At this critical moment for our ocean and our planet, our mission compels us to act on a greater scale than ever before.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: I'd like to hand it off now to Dr. Erin Meyer to share more about this important mission-driven work that is currently underway to conserve and protect our one world ocean.
